# Windows operator steps

This repo is edited on **macOS** (agent) and tested on **Windows** (operator). Use this rule when the operator needs to run or verify something on the Windows PC.

---

## When to include the section

End replies with **## What to do on your Windows machine** when:

| Situation | What to write |
|---|---|
| **Active Windows handoff** — agent pushed App/Spike changes, bug retest, spike, MSI, staging E2E | **One step only** (see below) |
| **Mac-only work** — Core tests, docs, plans, investigations, no Windows test yet | Brief: **Required now:** Nothing on Windows. Say when it will matter. |
| **Operator reported from Windows** — triage, next repro step, or waiting on Mac fix | **One step only** if they can do something now; otherwise explain wait state |

Do **not** list a full multi-step checklist in one reply during active handoff. The operator is a beginner — guide them **one step at a time**.

---

## One step at a time (active handoff)

During Mac ↔ Windows work:

1. Give **exactly one** action per reply (open, run, click, or verify).
2. End with: **Report back** — what to paste or describe (command output, error text, yes/no).
3. **Wait** for the operator’s reply before giving the next step.
4. On the next reply, acknowledge their result, then give **only** the next single step.

**Exception:** After an agent **push**, the first Windows step is always **pull latest** (one command block). Do not bundle pull + publish + run in the same reply unless the operator explicitly asks for the full sequence.

### PowerShell commands

- Put every Windows command in its **own** fenced code block tagged `powershell`.
- Commands must be **complete and copy-pasteable** — no `...`, no “then run the rest.”
- Say **where** to run it (e.g. “Open PowerShell in the repo folder”) before the block.
- One logical command (or one short sequence the operator runs as one paste) per block per step.

Example (good — one step):

```markdown
## What to do on your Windows machine

**Step 1 of sync** — confirm you are in the repo folder and fetch latest from GitHub.

Open PowerShell and run:

```powershell
cd C:\Users\Deon\event-platform-print-relay-windows
git fetch origin
```

**Report back:** Paste the full output (or say if you see an error).
```

Example (bad — do not do this during handoff):

```markdown
1. git pull
2. taskkill
3. dotnet publish
4. run exe
```

---

## Step content rules

1. **Plain English** — no jargon without a short explanation.
2. **Match the work** — tie the step to what changed or what you are debugging.
3. **Prerequisites first** — if staging, setup code, or a printer is needed, say so before the first actionable step.
4. **No secrets** — never ask the operator to paste relay secrets or full setup codes into chat.
5. **After agent push** — first step is pull/sync; give `git log -1 --oneline` as a separate step after pull so they can confirm SHA. Full sync sequence lives in `git-sync.mdc` — **split across replies**, not one wall of steps.

### Standard commands (reference — deliver one step at a time)

Pull (typical first step after push):

```powershell
cd C:\Users\Deon\event-platform-print-relay-windows
git fetch origin
git checkout feature/sprint-1-m1
git pull origin feature/sprint-1-m1
```

Confirm commit (separate step):

```powershell
git log -1 --oneline
```

Stop old app (before publish):

```powershell
taskkill /IM EventPlatform.PrintRelay.exe /F
```

Publish:

```powershell
dotnet publish src\EventPlatform.PrintRelay.App -c Release -r win-x64 --self-contained -o artifacts\app
```

Verify build:

```powershell
.\artifacts\app\EventPlatform.PrintRelay.exe --version
```

Run:

```powershell
.\artifacts\app\EventPlatform.PrintRelay.exe
```

Full detail: `.cursor/rules/git-sync.mdc`.

